== Life ==
Born in {{ill|Shimosuwa-shuku|ja|信濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}, a post station in the {{ill|Suwa region|ja|諏訪地方|12=draft|12=draft}}, Matsuzawa was the son of Shirōzaemon, a merchant dealing in gold, silver, and tortoiseshell. The family shop, known as Maruya, had ancestral roots in the {{ill|Iida-jō|ja|飯田城 (信濃国)|12=draft|12=draft}} area, engaging in trade between {{ill|Edo|ja|江戸|12=draft|12=draft}}, Suwa, and Iida. Matsuzawa studied {{ill|Confucianism|ja|儒学|12=draft|12=draft}} under {{ill|Sato Issai|ja|佐藤一斎|12=draft|12=draft}}.

At the age of 43 in {{ill|Tenpō 4|ja|天保4th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1833), Matsuzawa became a disciple of {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|平田篤胤|12=draft|12=draft}}, delving into kokugaku. He demonstrated deep knowledge of the {{ill|Spring and Autumn Annals|ja|春秋左氏伝|12=draft|12=draft}}, authoring *Shunju Taii* in {{ill|Tenpō 9|ja|天保9th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1838), where he critiqued errors in {{ill|Du Yu|ja|杜預|12=draft|12=draft}}'s *Chunqiu Jingzhuan Jiji*. In Edo, he associated with figures such as {{ill|Takano Chōei|ja|高野長英|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Mogami Tokunai|ja|最上徳内|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Hirata Kanetane|ja|平田銕胤|12=draft|12=draft}}, while in Suwa, he maintained ties with {{ill|Iida Takekuni|ja|飯田武郷|12=draft|12=draft}}. Matsuzawa was a proponent of imperial loyalty, becoming a foundational figure for kokugaku and imperial loyalist thought in the {{ill|Tenryū River|ja|天竜川|12=draft|12=draft}} region between Suwa and {{ill|Ina Valley|ja|伊那谷|12=draft|12=draft}}.

