At the age of 43 in {{ill|Tenpō 4|ja|天保4th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō 4|qq=}} (1833), Matsuzawa became a disciple of {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|平田篤胤|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirata Atsutane|qq=}}, delving into kokugaku. He demonstrated deep knowledge of the {{ill|Spring and Autumn Annals|ja|春秋左氏伝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Spring and Autumn Annals|qq=}}, authoring *Shunju Taii* in {{ill|Tenpō 9|ja|天保9th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō 9|qq=}} (1838), where he critiqued errors in {{ill|Du Yu|ja|杜預|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Du Yu|qq=}}'s *Chunqiu Jingzhuan Jiji*. In Edo, he associated with figures such as {{ill|Takano Chōei|ja|高野長英|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takano Chōei|qq=}}, {{ill|Mogami Tokunai|ja|最上徳内|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mogami Tokunai|qq=}}, and {{ill|Hirata Kanetane|ja|平田銕胤|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirata Kanetane|qq=}}, while in Suwa, he maintained ties with {{ill|Iida Takekuni|ja|飯田武郷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iida Takekuni|qq=}}. Matsuzawa was a proponent of imperial loyalty, becoming a foundational figure for kokugaku and imperial loyalist thought in the {{ill|Tenryū River|ja|天竜川|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenryū River|qq=}} region between Suwa and {{ill|Ina Valley|ja|伊那谷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ina Valley|qq=}}.

