{{Multiple issues |source=January 30, 2021 (Saturday) 20:17 (UTC) |citation=January 30, 2021 (Saturday) 20:17 (UTC) |sort_key=Person Died in 1861 }} '''Matsuzawa Yoshiakira''' (松沢 義章, 1791 - [[:en:1861|March 12, 1861]]) was a late [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] [[:en:Kokugaku|kokugaku]] scholar. His common name was Shirōzaemon, and his pen names included Gako Sanjin and Shunju no Sha.
== Life == Born in [[:en:Shinano Province|Shimosuwa-shuku]], a post station in the {{ill|Suwa Region|lt=Suwa Region|lt=Suwa region|ja|諏訪地方|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa region|qq=}}, Matsuzawa was the son of Shirōzaemon, a merchant dealing in gold, silver, and tortoiseshell. The family shop, known as Maruya, had ancestral roots in the {{ill|Iida-jō|ja|飯田城 (信濃国)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iida-jō|qq=}} area, engaging in trade between [[:en:Edo|Edo]], Suwa, and Iida. Matsuzawa studied {{ill|Confucianism|ja|儒学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Confucianism|qq=}} under [[:en:Satō Issai|Sato Issai]].
At the age of 43 in {{ill|Tenpō 4|ja|天保4年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō 4|qq=}} (1833), Matsuzawa became a disciple of [[:en:Hirata Atsutane|Hirata Atsutane]], delving into kokugaku. He demonstrated deep knowledge of the [[:en:Zuo Zhuan|Spring and Autumn Annals]], authoring *Shunju Taii* in {{ill|Tenpō 9|ja|天保9年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpō 9|qq=}} (1838), where he critiqued errors in [[:en:Du Yu|Du Yu]]'s *Chunqiu Jingzhuan Jiji*. In Edo, he associated with figures such as [[:en:Takano Chōei|Takano Chōei]], [[:en:Mogami Tokunai|Mogami Tokunai]], and {{ill|Hirata Kanetane|ja|平田銕胤|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirata Kanetane|qq=}}, while in Suwa, he maintained ties with {{ill|Iida Takekuni|ja|飯田武郷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iida Takekuni|qq=}}. Matsuzawa was a proponent of imperial loyalty, becoming a foundational figure for kokugaku and imperial loyalist thought in the [[:en:Tenryū River|Tenryū River]] region between Suwa and {{ill|Ina Valley|ja|伊那谷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ina Valley|qq=}}.
Known for his versatility, Matsuzawa also studied [[:en:Korean language|Korean language]], composing Japanese waka in {{ill|Hangul|ja|諺文|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hangul|qq=}}. He designed a steam bath kettle that was confiscated by the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|lt=Tokugawa shogunate|lt=Tokugawa Shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|lt=Tokugawa shogunate|lt=Tokugawa Shogunate|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Shogunate|qq=}}. In his later years, Matsuzawa turned his attention to local history, researching topics related to the [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]] and writing works such as *Suwa Kunikō*, *Suwa Koryōkō*, *Hōreishū*, and *Ken'yū Hongi*. He passed away in {{ill|Man'en 2|ja|万延2年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Man'en 2|qq=}} (1861) and was buried at [[:en:Dizang Temple|Jizō-ji]].
